    "No, there isn't any pure strategy Nash equilibrium of the game. This is because there simply doesn't exist one common outcome that both players would agree upon."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dried-charleston",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**(c) Is there any mixed strategy Nash equilibrium of the game? If so, find the equilibrium strategy of the game.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "communist-blocking",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Yes. Suppose Row assign probability $p$ to show heads, and probability $1-p$ to show tails; Column assign probability $q$ to show heads, and $1-q$ to show tails. Then given Column playing heads with prob. $q$, the expected return of Row by playing heads with prob. $p$ is\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\max_{p}v(q)&=pq*2+p(1-q)*(-1)+(1-p)q*(-1)+(1-p)(1-q)*2\\\\\n",
    "            &=p(6q-3)-3q+2.\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, Row would be indifferent in the choice of $p$ when $6q-3=0$, namely when $q=0.5$.  \n",
    "Now given Row playing heads with prob. $p$, the expected return of Column by playing heads with prob. $q$ is\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\max_{q}v(p)&=pq*(-1)+p(1-q)*(2)+(1-p)q*(2)+(1-p)(1-q)*(-2)\\\\\n",
    "            &=q(-7p+4)+4p-2\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, Row would be indifferent in the choice of $q$ when $-7p+4=0$, namely when $p=0.57$.  \n",
    "Hence, (Row Heads w.p. 0.57, Column Heads w.p. 0.5) is a mixed strategy N.E. of the game."
   ]
